05454nam a22008775i 9780823285518DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232855187 a10.1515/97808232855182doi  a(DE-B1597)555155  a(OCoLC)1109847174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a305.230822231 aGilmore, Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWitnessing Girlhood :bToward an Intersectional Tradition of Life Writing /cLeigh Gilmore, Elizabeth Marshall. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b12  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Witnessing Girlhood -- t1. Girls in Crisis: Feminist Resistance in Life Writing by Women of Color -- t2. Gender Pessimism and Survivor Storytelling in the Memoir Boom: Girl, Interrupted, Autobiography of a Face, and Nanette -- t3. Visualizing Sexual Violence and Feminist Child Witness: A Child’s Life and Other Stories and Becoming Unbecoming -- t4. Teaching Dissent through Picture Books: Girlhood Activism and Graphic Life Writing for the Child -- tEpilogue. Twenty-First-Century Formations: Child Witness, Trans Life Writing, and Futurity -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen more than 150 women testified in 2018 to the sexual abuse inflicted on them by Dr. Larry Nassar when they were young, competitive gymnasts, they exposed and transformed the conditions that shielded their violation, including the testimonial disadvantages that cluster at the site of gender, youth, and race. In Witnessing Girlhood, Leigh Gilmore and Elizabeth Marshall argue that they also joined a long tradition of autobiographical writing led by women of color in which adults use the figure and narrative of child witness to expose harm and seek justice. Witnessing Girlhood charts a history of how women use life narrative to transform conditions of suffering, silencing, and injustice into accounts that enjoin ethical response. Drawing on a deep and diverse archive of self-representational forms—slave narratives, testimonio, memoir, comics, and picture books—Gilmore and Marshall attend to how authors return to a narrative of traumatized and silenced girlhood and the figure of the child witness in order to offer public testimony. Emerging within these accounts are key scenes and figures that link a range of texts and forms from the mid–nineteenth century to the contemporary period. Gilmore and Marshall offer a genealogy of the reverberations across timelines, self-representational acts, and jurisdictions of the child witness in life writing. Reconstructing these historical and theoretical trajectories restores an intersectional testimonial history of writing by women of color about sexual and racist violence to the center of life writing and, in so doing, furthers our capacity to engage ethically with representations of vulnerability, childhood, and collective witness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAutobiographiesxWomen authors. 0aBiography as a literary form. 0aChild witnesses. 0aGirlsxSocial conditions. 0aMinority womenvBiography. 4aChildren’s Studies. 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh  aLife Writing.  achild activist.  achildhood.  acomics.  afeminist studies.  agraphic narrative.  apicture books.  asexual violence.  atestimony.  atrans childhood.  atrauma.  awitness literature.1 aMarshall, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru